{{Italic title}}'''''Typhoon of Steel''''' is a 1988 [[computer wargame]] designed by [[Gary Grigsby]] and published by [[Strategic Simulations|Strategic Simulations Inc.]] (SSI) for the [[Apple II series|Apple II]], [[Commodore 64]], [[Amiga]], and [[IBM PC compatible|IBM PC]]. A follow-up to Grigsby's 1987 game ''[[Panzer Strike]]'', it simulates military conflict during [[World War II]].

In 1989, ''Typhoon of Steel'' was followed by ''[[Overrun!]]'', which features an updated version of its [[Game engine|engine]] and mechanics. It simulated hypothetical conflicts in [[Europe]] and the [[Middle East]] during the [[Cold War]].

==Gameplay==
''Typhoon of Steel'' is a [[computer wargame]] that simulates military conflict during [[World War II]], covering combat scenarios in the [[Asiatic-Pacific Theater]] and [[European theatre of World War II|European Theatre]]. Alongside its pre-made scenarios, it features an [[Map editor|editor]] that allows players to create hypothetical battles.<ref name=vgce>{{cite journal | author=Katz, Arnie | title=Waging World War II: Military Simulations for Computers and Video Games | date=February 1989 | journal=[[VideoGames & Computer Entertainment]] | pages=76–82 }}</ref> ''Typhoon of Steel'' contains a "[[Banzai charge|Banzai]]" rule to impact games that become imbalanced.<ref name=cgw150/>

==Development==
''Typhoon of Steel'' was designed by [[Gary Grigsby]] and published by [[Strategic Simulations|Strategic Simulations Inc.]] (SSI).<ref name=brookssurvey>{{cite magazine | title=Brooks' Book Of Wargames: 1900-1950, R-Z | magazine=[[Computer Gaming World]] | issue=111 |date=October 1993 | author=Brooks, M. Evan | pages=144–148}}</ref> A sequel to Grigsby's game ''[[Panzer Strike]]'',<ref name=computerplayrev /><ref name=vgce/> it reuses that project's [[game engine]] and [[Game mechanics|mechanics]],<ref name=zzap>{{cite journal | author=Hogg, Robin | title=''Overrun!'' | date=July 1989 | journal=[[Zzap!64|Zzap!]] | issue=51 | page=61 }}</ref> updated to focus on different sections of World War II. This design reuse followed a common trend for SSI titles at the time: the game systems of successful titles were often reused in subsequent products.<ref name=computerplayrev>{{cite journal | author=Ceccola, Russ | title=Another WWII Winner from SSI | date=January 1989 | journal=Computer Play | pages=18, 20 }}</ref> Like its predecessor, ''Typhoon of Steel'' debuted in 1988.<ref name=guru>{{cite magazine | author=Emrich, Alan | title=The Pioneering Spirit of a Wargame Guru | date=September 1995 | issue=134 | magazine=[[Computer Gaming World]] | pages=201, 202, 204 }}</ref>

