M. Evan Brooks reviewed the game for ''[[Computer Gaming World]]'', and stated that "for the dedicated gamer, ''Typhoon of Steel'' offers an engaging, albeit time-consuming, study of small unit actions during World War II in the South Pacific."<ref name="CGW54">{{cite magazine |last=Brooks |first=M. Evan |title=Banzai Strike Line: Pacific Theater Combat in "Typhoon of Steel" |magazine=Computer Gaming World |date=December 1988 |volume=1 |issue=54 |pages=32–34}}</ref>

In ''Computer Play'', Russ Ceccola offered ''Typhoon of Steel'' a positive review and recommended it to "the serious war gamer".<ref name=computerplayrev /> ''[[Computer Gaming World]]'' nominated ''Typhoon of Steel'' for its "Wargame of the Year" award, which ultimately went to ''[[Battles of Napoleon]]''.<ref name=cgw1989>{{cite magazine | author=Editorial Staff | title=Game of the Year Awards | issue=64 | date=October 1989 | magazine=[[Computer Gaming World]] | pages=8, 41, 42 }}</ref>

Reviewing the Amiga version, George Campbell of ''[[Strategy Plus]]'' dubbed ''Typhoon of Steel'' "an excellent game".<ref name=strategyplus>{{cite journal | author=Campbell, George | title=Strategy; ''Typhoon of Steel'' | journal=[[Strategy Plus]] | issue=6 | date=March 1991 | pages=12, 13 }}</ref> ''[[Zzap!64|Zzap!]]''{{'}}s reviewer considered the game flawed, but noted that it contained "a lot of worthwhile detail" and "plenty of ambition".<ref name=zzap2 />

==Legacy==
''Typhoon of Steel'' was followed by ''[[Overrun!]]'', which reused the game's mechanics and engine, updated to focus on modern warfare scenarios.<ref name=zzap />

In 1996, ''Computer Gaming World'' declared ''Typhoon of Steel'' the 143rd-best computer game ever released.<ref name=cgw150>{{cite magazine | author=Staff | title=150 Best (and 50 Worst) Games of All Time | magazine=[[Computer Gaming World]] | date=November 1996 | issue=148 | pages=63–65, 68, 72, 74, 76, 78, 80, 84, 88, 90, 94, 98 }}</ref>

